<title>C&#45;&#45;D</title>
<path fill="none" stroke="#000000" d="M68.0768,-41.3457C106.163,-52.5023 178.1619,-73.5929 216.1268,-84.7139" />
</g>
<!-- F -->
<g id="node6" class="node">
<title>F</title>
<ellipse fill="none" stroke="#000000" cx="241" cy="-34" rx="27" ry="18" />
<text text-anchor="middle" x="241" y="-29.8" font-family="Times,serif" font-size="14.00" fill="#000000">F</text>
</g>
<!-- C&#45;&#45;F -->
<g id="edge5" class="edge">
<title>C&#45;&#45;F</title>
<path fill="none" stroke="#000000" d="M70.1159,-34C107.9267,-34 176.0895,-34 213.8946,-34" />
</g>
</g>
</svg>
</div>

<p>The thin black edges have cost 1, and the thick red edge has cost 2. The Hungarian algorithm uses the <a href="#lemma:min-cost-perfect-matching-and-dual-solution">lemma from above</a> to always keep a dual solution $y = (u, v)$ that is <em>feasible at all times</em>. For any fixed dual solution, the lemma tells us that the perfect matching can only contain <strong>tight edges</strong>, which are edges $e = (a, b)$ for which $u_a + v_b = c(e)$.</p>

<p>The Hungarian algorithm initializes the vertex weights to the following trivial solutions:</p>

\[v_b = 0, \quad
u_a = \min_{b \in B} c_{ab}\]

<p>The right vertices get weight 0, and the left vertices get the weight of the smallest edge they’re incident to. The weights $u$ and $v$, and the set of tight edges $E’$ is displayed below.</p>

<div class="diagrams graphviz"><svg width="304pt" height="221pt" viewBox="0.00 0.00 304.33 221.00" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
<g id="graph0" class="graph" transform="scale(1 1) rotate(0) translate(4 217)">
<title>G</title>
